"pours a partly hazy very pale, straw yellow with medium soft white head. not a whole lot of head retention, but nice lacing on the glass. loads of soft wheaty aroma with hints of lemon zest and a bit of honey. smells very clean. on the palate there is a definite sourness that strikes first although somewhat light--any more would turn it into a berliner weisse. tastes very reminiscent of a radler (half beer and half lemonade). practically thin as water. alcohol not apparent at all. carbonation diminishes quickly. the longer you take to drink it, the more it loses its 'snap'. definitely a beer for quaffing down quickly on a hot summer day. all in all, a very refreshing beer that performs well in the heat of summer."
"Am I the only one who really doesn't like New Belgium's ""new"" branding? Regardless, this stuff pours a cloudy pale straw topped by a finger-and-a-half of white foam. The nose comprises lemon zest and light flowers. Anything else disappears into the small ether space between the surface and my 'strils. The taste brings in more of the same, though the lemon here is fairly tart. Didn't see that coming, honestly. The body is a hefty light, with a light moderate carbonation and a fluid feel. Overall, a surprisingly sour wheat, one that I could easily see drinking more of in the near future."
""
"O - This is a fairly typical wheat beer, with a subtle souring, perhaps too subtle. The citrus is limited, and I found most of the flavors fairly muted. No missteps, just not terribly interesting."
"O - Not only does New Belgium have a penchant for constantly creating new extremely drinkable summertime beers but they also have a big love for sours. While sours have exploded in popularity in the craft beer community, they're not quite ready for the mainstream and that's where Snapshot comes in. New Belgium's Snapshot takes everything great about a pale wheat ale; it's drinkability, refreshing quality, and light, sessionable flavor and adds a twist of tart lactobacillus, a souring bacteria. For us exploratory drinkers it's reminiscent of a German Berliner Weisse while it maintains great training wheel characteristics for those uninitiated looking to get their feet wet in the wild world of sours. Like many of their lighter offerings usually do during the warmer months, Snapshot will have a permanent place in my fridge this summer."
